    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix socket resource leak in NGAP overload message handling\n\n### Summary\nThe NGAP overload handling functions `ngap_gNB_handle_overload_start` and `ngap_gNB_handle_overload_stop` were not properly implemented, causing socket resource leaks when overload messages were received. The handler table had NULL entries for these message types, meaning overload conditions were not being processed at all.\n\nThis fix implements proper handling of NGAP OverloadStart and OverloadStop messages, ensuring that socket resources are properly managed and the gNB can respond appropriately to AMF overload conditions.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NGAP/ngap_gNB_overload.c`: Implemented `ngap_gNB_handle_overload_start` function to properly parse OverloadStart messages and update AMF state. Enhanced `ngap_gNB_handle_overload_stop` with proper error handling.\n- `openair3/NGAP/ngap_gNB_handlers.c`: Updated message handler table to register the overload functions instead of having NULL handlers.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure an AMF to send OverloadStart messages to the gNB\n2. Monitor socket resource usage during overload conditions\n3. Observe that without the fix, socket descriptors may not be properly managed during overload handling, leading to resource exhaustion\n\nThe fix ensures that overload messages are properly processed and socket resources are maintained correctly throughout the overload handling flow.\n"
}